{
  "doc_id": "27703",
  "text": "This convergence of evidence indicates that hemispheric organization of motor and speech functions are related, to the extent that the functional status of one is associated with the cortical representation of the other. This relationship has primarily been examined in cohorts with a predominant language disorder. To date, this relationship has not been examined in individuals with a predominant motor disorder, such as those seen in developmental coordination disorder (DCD), but without co-occurring language or reading impairments. This is a surprising omission in the light of existing theories of how language and motor systems co-exist with regard to the neural networks underpinning them [CITATION_1] .",
